<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="310" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,657,1943]" pageId="9" pageNumber="310">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1808,1835]" pageId="9" pageNumber="310">Comments.</emphasis>
Within the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Amyot &amp; Serville" authorityYear="1843" box="[543,678,1809,1835]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Hoplothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="310" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[543,678,1809,1835]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="310">Hoplothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
this species is unusual in having a maxillary bridge. It is generally similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hood" authorityYear="1919" box="[266,405,1846,1871]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Trichothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="310" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="connexus">
<emphasis box="[266,405,1846,1871]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="310">H. connexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but with shorter median setae on tergites II–VII, and the macroptera has two pairs of welldeveloped sigmoid wing-retaining setae. The pore plate on sternite VIII of the male is transverse but present only on the median third of the sternite, and sternite VII has no specialised reticulate areas laterally.
</paragraph>
